Project 3 - Directory Traversal Attack (FTP/HTTP Lab)
Overview

This project demonstrates a directory traversal attack against a vulnerable server. The goal is to understand how improper input validation can allow unauthorized access to restricted files outside of the intended directory.

Objective:
 *Use a Bash script to automate HTTP requests
 *Perform directory traversal using ../ sequences
 *Identify sensitive files accessible due to misconfigured access controls
 *Analyze server behavior and responses

Tools Used:
 *Bash (attack.sh)
 *curl
 *hftp vulnerable server

Files Included:
 *attack.sh – Bash script used to launch directory traversal attempts against the vulnerable server

Methodology:
 *A vulnerable local server was started using hftp.
 *A Bash script was executed to send multiple crafted HTTP requests.
 *Directory traversal patterns (../) were used to attempt access to restricted directories.
 *Responses were analyzed to determine which files were successfully accessed.
 *The server process was terminated after testing.
Key Concept:
Directory traversal occurs when an attacker is able to manipulate file paths using sequences like ../ to move outside of the intended directory structure and access sensitive files.

Outcome:
The script successfully demonstrated how insecure file access controls can expose restricted files on a server.

Notes:
This project was completed in a controlled lab environment for educational purposes only.
